card.how:
`do` block:
```
do {
  var discount = if (payload.tier == 'GOLD') 0.2 else 0.1
  var base = payload.price
  ---
  { finalPrice: base * (1 - discount), tier: payload.tier }
}
```
Dynamic keys:
```
// config list → map object
{(payload.config map { ($.key): $.value })}
// group + pivot
payload groupBy $.region mapObject (rows, region) -> {
  (region): { total: sum(rows map $.amount) }
}
```
flatten / flatMap:
```
flatten([[1,2],[3,4]])           // [1,2,3,4]
payload.orders flatMap $.items   // all items across all orders
```
try():
```
try(() -> read(item.meta, 'application/json')) match {
  case { success: true  } -> $.result
  case { success: false } -> { error: $.error.message }
}
```

card.deep_dive:
**`do` vs module function:** `do` is inline and single-use. Module functions are for reuse across transforms. Rule: if you write the same logic twice, extract it to a module.

**flatMap vs map+flatten:** `flatMap` is syntactic sugar for one-level flatten after map. Prefer it when you know flattening is needed. Use separate `flatten(map(...))` when the steps are conceptually distinct.

**`try()` in production — critical pattern for nested JSON parsing:**
```
payload map (item) ->
  try(() -> read(item.meta, 'application/json')) match {
    case { success: true  } -> { (item) parsedMeta: $.result }
    case { success: false } -> { (item) parsedMeta: null, metaError: $.error.message }
  }
```
Without `try()`, one malformed `meta` field crashes the entire transform. With it, bad records are flagged and processing continues — essential for batch pipelines.
